---
/**
 * CLUSTER E - Comparativos Anti-Narrativa
 * Página: /en/compare/deep-plane-without-150k-tower/
 * Prioridade: P0
 * Intenção: Dor central - anti-sequestro de narrativa
 */
import BaseLayout from '@layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Breadcrumb from '@components/ui/Breadcrumb.astro';
import SchemaArticle from '@components/seo/SchemaArticle.astro';
import SchemaFAQ from '@components/seo/SchemaFAQ.astro';

const breadcrumbs = [
  { name: 'Home', url: '/' },
  { name: 'Compare', url: '/compare' },
  { name: 'Deep Plane Without $150k Tower', url: '/compare/deep-plane-without-150k-tower' },
];

const keywords = [
  'deep plane facelift without endoscope',
  'facelift without expensive equipment',
  'affordable facelift technique',
  'midface lift cost',
  'facial surgery equipment cost',
  'direct vision facelift',
];

const faqItems = [
  {
    question: 'Do you really need a $150,000 endoscopic tower for deep plane surgery?',
    answer:
      "No. The endoscopic tower enables visualization in spaces where direct line-of-sight isn't possible. But for midface surgery, proper incision placement allows Direct Vision — direct visualization without cameras. Dr. Brandão's ENDOMIDFACE technique achieves deep plane-level results with equipment costing under $5,000 total (loupes, headlight, instruments). 1,500+ surgeries with zero permanent nerve injuries validate this approach.",
  },
  {
    question: 'Is Direct Vision surgery lower quality than endoscopic?',
    answer:
      "No. Direct Vision actually provides advantages: 3D stereoscopic vision (vs 2D screen), zero latency, full tactile feedback, no equipment failure risk. The question isn't which has more technology, but which provides better anatomical control. For midface lifting, Direct Vision often wins. The technique's safety record and outcomes data support this.",
  },
  {
    question: 'Why do some surgeons insist on expensive equipment?',
    answer:
      'Several reasons: training (they learned on endoscopes), marketing (expensive = advanced perception), genuine preference for camera visualization, or cases where endoscopy is truly necessary. None of these mean Direct Vision is inferior. Equipment should serve the surgical goal, not define it.',
  },
  {
    question:
      'Can surgeons in developing countries or smaller practices achieve excellent facial rejuvenation?',
    answer:
      'Absolutely. This is exactly why Dr. Brandão developed ENDOMIDFACE by Direct Vision — working in Natal, Brazil without access to expensive equipment. The technique democratizes advanced facial surgery. Over 130 surgeons from 7+ countries have been trained, many from resource-limited settings who report excellent results.',
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Can You Do Deep Plane Without a $150k Tower? — The Direct Vision Answer"
  description="The equipment-free path to advanced facial surgery. Learn how ENDOMIDFACE® by Direct Vision achieves deep plane-level results without endoscopic equipment. Safety data, cost comparison, and clinical evidence."
  keywords={keywords}
>
  <SchemaArticle
    title="Can You Do Deep Plane Without a $150k Tower?"
    description="Examining equipment requirements for advanced facial surgery and the Direct Vision alternative"
    section="Technical Comparison"
    keywords={keywords}
    articleType="MedicalWebPage"
  />
  <SchemaFAQ items={faqItems} />

  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="py-16 bg-primary-900">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6">
      <Breadcrumb items={breadcrumbs} class="text-primary-300 mb-8" />

      <p class="text-accent-400 text-sm font-semibold tracking-wider uppercase mb-4">
        The Central Question
      </p>
      <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-serif text-white mb-6">
        Can You Do Deep Plane Without a $150k Tower?
      </h1>
      <p class="text-2xl text-primary-200 font-serif italic mb-4">
        Yes. And the safety record proves it.
      </p>
      <p class="text-xl text-primary-300">
        The assumption that advanced facial surgery requires expensive endoscopic equipment is
        widespread but wrong. Here's the evidence.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- The Assumption -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-ivory">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6">
      <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-serif text-primary-900 mb-8">
        The Expensive Equipment Assumption
      </h2>

      <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none text-warmGray">
        <p class="text-xl leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Walk into many facial surgery conversations and you'll encounter a implicit assumption: <em
            >serious facial rejuvenation requires serious equipment investment.</em
          >
        </p>

        <p class="mb-6">
          The logic seems reasonable. Endoscopes provide visualization in deep spaces. Deep plane
          surgery works in deep spaces. Therefore, deep plane surgery needs endoscopes. Investment
          range: $100,000-$150,000 for a proper tower setup with camera, monitor, light source, and
          specialized instruments.
        </p>

        <p class="mb-6">This assumption creates real consequences:</p>

        <ul class="space-y-3 mb-6">
          <li>
            <strong>Surgeons in resource-limited settings</strong> believe advanced facial surgery is
            beyond their reach
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>New practitioners</strong> delay offering comprehensive facial rejuvenation until
            they can afford equipment
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Established surgeons</strong> hesitate to evolve their techniques if it means massive
            capital investment
          </li>
          <li><strong>Patients</strong> pay premium prices that include equipment amortization</li>
        </ul>

        <p class="mb-6">
          But what if the assumption is wrong? What if the equipment isn't necessary for the
          results?
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- The Evidence -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-white">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-serif text-primary-900 mb-8">The Evidence Against the Assumption</h2>

      <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none text-warmGray">
        <p class="mb-6">
          <a href="/creator" class="text-accent-600 hover:text-accent-700 underline"
            >Dr. Robério Brandão</a
          > has performed over <strong>1,500 facial surgeries</strong> using <a
            href="/methods/endomidface-direct-vision"
            class="text-accent-600 hover:text-accent-700 underline">Direct Vision techniques</a
          > — no endoscopic tower required.
        </p>

        <div class="bg-accent-50 border-l-4 border-accent-500 p-6 my-8">
          <p class="font-bold text-primary-900 text-xl mb-2">The Safety Record</p>
          <ul class="space-y-1 text-warmGray">
            <li>• <strong>1,500+</strong> surgeries performed</li>
            <li>• <strong>Zero</strong> permanent motor nerve injuries</li>
            <li>• <strong>&lt;2%</strong> transient weakness (all resolved)</li>
            <li>• <strong>130+</strong> surgeons trained, replicating results</li>
            <li>• <strong>18 years</strong> of documented outcomes</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <p class="mb-6">
          This isn't theory. This is <a
            href="/creator/case-series-safety"
            class="text-accent-600 hover:text-accent-700 underline">documented clinical data</a
          >. The technique works. The safety record matches or exceeds published benchmarks for
          endoscopic approaches. And it's reproducible — trained surgeons report similar outcomes.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-serif text-primary-900 mt-10 mb-4">Why Direct Vision Works</h3>

        <p class="mb-6">
          The key insight is simple: <strong
            >endoscopes solve a visualization problem that doesn't exist in midface surgery</strong
          > when incisions are properly placed.
        </p>

        <p class="mb-6">
          The temporal incision used in ENDOMIDFACE® provides direct line-of-sight to the
          subperiosteal plane of the midface. You're not working in a space that's invisible without
          a camera — you're working in a space that's directly accessible. The camera doesn't add
          visualization; it substitutes a 2D screen for 3D direct vision.
        </p>

        <p class="mb-6">
          For detailed physics explanation, see: <a
            href="/methods/endomidface/direct-vision-vs-endoscopic"
            class="text-accent-600 hover:text-accent-700 underline"
            >Direct Vision vs Endoscopic Tower: Myth vs Reality</a
          >
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Cost Comparison -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-primary-50">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-serif text-primary-900 mb-8 text-center">
        The Real Cost Comparison
      </h2>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8 mb-8">
        <div class="p-8 bg-white border-2 border-green-200 rounded-xl">
          <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-green-600 mb-2">Direct Vision Approach</p>
          <h3 class="text-4xl font-bold text-green-700 mb-4">$1,600 - $5,000</h3>
          <p class="text-sm text-warmGray mb-4">Total equipment investment</p>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-green-700 text-sm">
            <li>✓ Surgical loupes (3.5x magnification)</li>
            <li>✓ LED headlight</li>
            <li>✓ Specialized instruments</li>
            <li>✓ Zero ongoing maintenance</li>
            <li>✓ Portable to any facility</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="p-8 bg-white border-2 border-red-200 rounded-xl">
          <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-red-600 mb-2">Endoscopic Approach</p>
          <h3 class="text-4xl font-bold text-red-700 mb-4">$85,000 - $150,000</h3>
          <p class="text-sm text-warmGray mb-4">Tower setup investment</p>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-red-700 text-sm">
            <li>• Camera system + processor</li>
            <li>• Monitor system</li>
            <li>• Light source</li>
            <li>• Specialized instruments</li>
            <li>• Ongoing calibration/maintenance</li>
            <li>• Fixed OR location</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none text-warmGray">
        <p class="text-center">
          The cost difference is <strong>30-90x</strong>. If outcomes are equivalent, where does the
          value of the additional investment come from?
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Who This Matters For -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-white">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-serif text-primary-900 mb-8">Who This Matters For</h2>

      <div class="space-y-6">
        <div class="p-6 bg-ivory rounded-xl">
          <h3 class="font-bold text-primary-900 text-lg mb-2">Surgeons in Developing Countries</h3>
          <p class="text-warmGray">
            $150,000 represents an impossible barrier for many excellent surgeons outside wealthy
            markets. Direct Vision removes this barrier, allowing access to advanced facial surgery
            techniques without capital investment that may never be recoverable.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="p-6 bg-ivory rounded-xl">
          <h3 class="font-bold text-primary-900 text-lg mb-2">
            New Practitioners Building a Practice
          </h3>
          <p class="text-warmGray">
            Early-career surgeons can offer comprehensive facial rejuvenation immediately rather
            than waiting years to accumulate capital for equipment. Start treating patients now;
            evolve your offerings based on clinical need, not equipment availability.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="p-6 bg-ivory rounded-xl">
          <h3 class="font-bold text-primary-900 text-lg mb-2">
            Established Surgeons Questioning Equipment ROI
          </h3>
          <p class="text-warmGray">
            If you've been considering an endoscopic purchase, consider whether Direct Vision
            achieves your goals more efficiently. The technique may render the investment
            unnecessary — and the saved capital can improve your practice in other ways.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="p-6 bg-ivory rounded-xl">
          <h3 class="font-bold text-primary-900 text-lg mb-2">
            Surgeons Who Already Have Endoscopes
          </h3>
          <p class="text-warmGray">
            Learning Direct Vision doesn't mean abandoning endoscopy where it's genuinely valuable.
            It means having another tool — one that's faster to deploy, has zero failure risk, and
            may provide better visualization for certain procedures.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FAQ Section -->
  <section class="py-16 bg-ivory">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-serif text-primary-900 mb-8">Common Questions</h2>

      <div class="space-y-6">
        {
          faqItems.map((item) => (
            <div class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm overflow-hidden">
              <div class="p-6">
                <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-primary-900 mb-3">{item.question}</h3>
                <p class="text-warmGray">{item.answer}</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          ))
        }
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- The Invitation -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-white">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-serif text-primary-900 mb-8">The Invitation</h2>

      <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none text-warmGray">
        <p class="mb-6">
          We're not asking you to take this on faith. We're asking you to examine the evidence:
        </p>

        <ul class="space-y-2 mb-6">
          <li>
            Review the <a
              href="/creator/case-series-safety"
              class="text-accent-600 hover:text-accent-700 underline">safety data</a
            >
          </li>
          <li>
            Understand the <a
              href="/methods/endomidface/direct-vision-vs-endoscopic"
              class="text-accent-600 hover:text-accent-700 underline">technical comparison</a
            >
          </li>
          <li>
            Learn about the <a
              href="/creator/timeline"
              class="text-accent-600 hover:text-accent-700 underline">development history</a
            >
          </li>
          <li>
            Talk to <a
              href="/creator/trained-surgeons"
              class="text-accent-600 hover:text-accent-700 underline"
              >surgeons who've been trained</a
            >
          </li>
        </ul>

        <p class="mb-6">
          If you conclude that expensive equipment is necessary for your practice, that's a valid
          choice. But make it based on evidence, not assumption. The assumption that advanced facial
          surgery requires advanced equipment investment is testable — and the evidence suggests
          it's wrong.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CTA -->
  <section class="py-16 bg-primary-900">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 text-center">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-serif text-white mb-4">Learn the Equipment-Free Approach</h2>
      <p class="text-xl text-primary-200 mb-8">
        ENDOMIDFACE® mentorship teaches Direct Vision technique with complete anatomical training
        and ongoing mentorship support.
      </p>
      <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row justify-center gap-4">
        <a
          href="/training"
          class="inline-flex items-center justify-center gap-2 px-8 py-4 bg-accent-500 text-white rounded-lg hover:bg-accent-600 transition-colors font-semibold text-lg"
        >
          Training Programs
        </a>
        <a
          href="/methods/endomidface-direct-vision"
          class="inline-flex items-center justify-center gap-2 px-8 py-4 border border-white/30 text-white rounded-lg hover:bg-white/10 transition-colors text-lg"
        >
          ENDOMIDFACE® Overview
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
